    "Step 1: Thinking\n  [{ Id = 1d52470d-dcfa-49b2-9f12-58b1572f3b2f\n     CorrelationId = CorrelationId 8761e806-ef57-4201-997e-35f19d87f8ba\n     Sender = System\n     Receiver = Some (Agent (AgentId 47aa0d71-5fdc-41a0-bdb1-7bf17af1b073))\n     Performative = Request\n     Intent = Some Coding\n     Constraints = { MaxTokens = None\n                     MaxComplexity = None\n                     Timeout = None\n                     KnowledgeBoundary = [] }\n     Ontology = None\n     Language = \u0022text\u0022\n     Content =\n      \u0022To calculate the factorial of a number using recursion in F#, I\u0027ll follow these steps:\n\n1. Define the function signature.\n2. Implement the base case for 0.\n3. Handle negative numbers by returning an error or a specific value.\n4. Implement the recursive case.\n\nHere\u0027s the implementation:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\nlet rec factorial n =\n    match n with\n    | 0 -\u003E 1\n    | _ when n \u003C 0 -\u003E failwith \u0022Factorial is not defined for negative numbers\u0022\n    | _ -\u003E n * factorial (n - 1)\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nThis function uses pattern matching to handle the base case and recursion. It also includes a check for negative numbers, which will raise an error if encountered.\n\nTo validate this function, I\u0027ll write a few test cases:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\nlet testFactorial =\n    let tests = [\n        (0, 1)\n        (1, 1)\n        (5, 120)\n        (-1, failwith \u0022Expected error for negative input\u0022)\n    ]\n\n    let runTests () =\n        tests |\u003E List.iter (fun (input, expected) -\u003E\n            try\n                let result = factorial input\n                if result \u003C\u003E expected then\n                    printfn \u0022Test failed: Input %d, Expected %d, Got %d\u0022 input expected result\n                else\n                    printfn \u0022Test passed: Input %d, Result %d\u0022 input result\n            with\n            | ex -\u003E \n       